**Pokémon Studio 3.0 is coming soon** , and with it, a real turning point for the community. For years, RPG Maker XP (RMXP) has been the go-to tool for building events in Pokémon fangames.   
But times have changed.   
Here’s **why we’ve decided to move on and what we’re building with you** for the future.

## A Major Step Forward for Pokémon Studio

With version 2.0, **Tiled became the official tool for map creation** in PSDK. That was already a big step forward. Goodbye to RMXP’s outdated map editor.

But one key part was still tied to RMXP: **event management**.

Pokémon Studio 3.0 introduces:

- A brand-new event system **built right into Studio**
- A modern interface, made for **no-code or low-code workflows**
- The ability to build a fangame **without relying on outdated or paid tools**

It’s one more step toward a tool that’s **free, accessible, and 100% tailored to Pokémon fangames**.

## Why We’re Retiring RPG Maker XP (and What We’re Doing Better)

RPG Maker XP had its moment but it’s no longer fit for today’s needs.

Here’s a quick breakdown of **RMXP’s limitations** , and how Pokémon Studio 3.0 addresses them.

### RMXP Limitation

- Fixed, non-responsive interface
- Outdated event editor with no search or categories
- Script command limitations (length, readability, layout)
- Weak condition logic (no advanced logic support)
- Not built for today’s users
- Paid, closed-source software

### What Studio 3.0 Delivers

- Modern, readable, responsive UI
- Structured UI with search, grouping, and filters
- A proper script editor: syntax highlighting, full width, clean UX
- Fully flexible, nestable, combinable conditions
- UX based on real feedback from modern-day fangame creators
- Pokémon Studio is **open source and free**

## What We’re Building with Pokémon Studio

We’re not just giving RMXP a fresh coat of paint.  
We’re **starting from scratch** , with a clear vision built **on your feedback**.

 

Here are the core principles behind the redesign:

### A Clean, Intuitive UX

- No more messy lists of ungrouped commands
- Events are **organized** , with **built-in search** and **clear categories**
- A guided editing experience that still respects creative freedom

### A Smart Script Command

- Syntax highlighting
- No arbitrary character limits
- Better UX, with smart encouragements to **modularize your systems cleanly**

### Powerful, Flexible Conditions

- Logical combinations (AND, OR)
- Condition nesting
- Advanced options like Pokémon level, inventory items, weather checks, and more

### Less Hacking, More Native Power

- Say goodbye to hardcoded tags and undocumented workarounds
- Our goal: **make everything configurable through the UI**

## Why It’s Taking Time (And Why That’s a Good Thing)

Events are the **core of your game** : dialogue, cutscenes, interactions…

 

We can’t afford to rush it. We’d rather:

- Build a **solid foundation**
- Create a system that can **scale over time**
- Take the time to design a UX that **truly fits how you work**

This isn’t **lost time**. It’s an **investment in your future**. One that avoids giving you a frustrating tool from the start.

## Pokémon Studio 3.0 Will Be an MVP (And That’s Okay!)

When Pokémon Studio 3.0 launches, it **won’t be the final version**.

It’ll be a **functional** , **stable** , but **minimal** first release: A **Minimum Viable Product (MVP)**, just enough to build, test, and start creating.

What’s next?  
👉 Frequent updates whenever we can, with **ongoing improvements** based on your feedback (QoL upgrades, new commands, advanced options, etc.)

This approach lets us:

- Deliver faster, with more focus
- Get the community involved early
- Build something **with you** , one step at a time

## A Community-Led Effort

We’re not building in a vacuum.   
 Over the coming weeks, here’s what you can expect:

- **Real previews** : screenshots, demos, UI walkthroughs
- **A community testing phase** : for those who want to contribute, report bugs, or share ideas
- **Live discussions** on Discord, with dedicated channels for feedback

Your input directly shapes what we build.

## An Open-Source Project, Open to Everyone

Pokémon Studio is a **free and open-source tool** , developed **transparently and collaboratively**.

Whether you’re a developer, designer, tester, writer or just curious, you can help out!

Every contribution matters, even a simple typo fix or UX suggestion.

Check out our [GitHub](https://github.com/PokemonWorkshop/PokemonStudio/) or join the conversation on [Discord](https://discord.gg/0noB0gBDd91B8pMk) to get involved.

Our tech stack: React, TypeScript, Electron, Figma (UI design), Miro (whiteboarding & workshops).

## Thank You to the Community

What we’re building isn’t just an event editor.

It’s a tool to make **Pokémon fangame creation simpler, freer, and more modern**.

And it’s only possible thanks to your ideas, feedback, messages and your patience.

What’s next for Pokémon Studio?

**We’re writing it together.**

